# App Launch — Prioritized To-Do List

---

## 🔴 Pre-Launch (Bug Fixes & Critical Issues)

- [ ] **Offline mode UI** — Move retry button and banner lower so they display correctly on all screen sizes
- [ ] **Batch claiming bug** — Fix claim reverting after a split second; ensure claimed batches populate the "My Batches" tab correctly
- [ ] **Voice command notification** — Resolve "voice command not enabled" error; add voice control support for timer (start, pause, stop, etc.)
- [ ] **App load time** — Reduce time-to-home-screen to 3 seconds or less; investigate faster internet connectivity detection to minimize online/offline polling delay

---

## ⏪ Pending Rollback (App Stability — Local-First Restore)

> These changes made during the Feb 2026 development session degraded app performance and reliability. The app must be restored to local-first architecture before continuing other feature work.

**Prompt for rollback session:**
> "We need to roll back the app's data layer to local-first architecture. The app was fast and reliable when it used in-memory cache + AsyncStorage as the source of truth, with Supabase as a background sync target only. Recent changes made Supabase the primary data source, causing slow screen loads, broken batch claiming, broken voice recognition, and a broken 'My Batches' tab. The target commit is `a26cef0` (RELEASE BUILD) for the core data logic. Restore `services/database.ts` to that version's architecture — local cache is king, Supabase writes are fire-and-forget and never block the UI. Then add a clean background push layer for: batch create/update/delete, batch claiming (claimed_by, claimed_by_name columns), and workflow changes. The website reads from Supabase so it stays up to date, but the app never waits on Supabase for anything."

**Specific things to restore/fix:**
- [ ] `services/database.ts` — restore local-first cache as source of truth, Supabase writes are background only
- [ ] Remove 3-second polling `loadData()` loop that hammers Supabase on every tick in `WorkflowSelectScreen`
- [ ] `claimBatch` — update local cache immediately, push to Supabase in background (fire-and-forget)
- [ ] `_refreshBatches` — should hydrate from local AsyncStorage on launch, not block on Supabase
- [ ] Voice recognition — regression introduced during refactor; restore working state from `a26cef0`
- [ ] "My Batches" tab — should filter from local cache using `claimed_by === currentUserId`, not rely on Supabase query result
- [ ] Remove any UI-blocking `await` calls to Supabase in the hot path (screen load, navigation, batch operations)

**New columns added to Supabase `batches` table that must be preserved in the background sync:**
- `owner_id` (uuid) — set on batch creation, never changes
- `claimed_by` (uuid) — who is currently working the batch
- `claimed_by_name` (text) — display name of claimer

---

## 🟠 Pre-Launch (Core Features)

- [ ] **Account tiers** — Maintain two separate account pages (standard and premium); standard users should not see premium/production tools to avoid overwhelm as well as maintain value in the premium service
- [ ] **Location locking** — Employees can only clock in within a set radius (~100m) of the registered business address
  - Food trucks: when start-of-day report is submitted, record a location ping; all staff must check in within ~100m of that ping
  - Multiple trucks require separate licenses; no simultaneous sign-in across physically separate locations
  - Ghost kitchens operating multiple brands from one address are fine on a single license (data will not be separated by brand)
- [ ] **Workflow caching & directory** — Store all workflows created or imported by free-tier users; cache parsed results to avoid duplicate AI parse costs; build a browsable workflow directory (e.g. "Browse Directory" or "Import Workflow")
  - Enforce no blog post attachments
  - Only scrape recipe ingredients and steps (not blog content — copyright risk)
  - Parse workflows for equipment references (required vs. recommended)
- [ ] **Barcode printing (web portal)** — Print barcodes tied to active batches; scanning with the app shows batch details (workflow, current step, timer, claimed status) and allows claiming. Printing the barcode should release that workflow from any user that has claimed it.
- [ ] **New user tutorial** — Interactive onboarding walkthrough for first-time users

---

## 🟡 Post-Launch (Growth Features)

- [ ] **POS integration** — Connect to major POS systems (Square, Toast, Lightspeed, Clover, etc.) to pull in sales data for costing and revenue analytics; export data in appropriate formats (CSV, XLSX, etc.)
- [ ] **Web embed tool** — Paid embeddable widget for third-party websites to display workflow operations (branded "Powered by Batch Maker" or similar)
- [ ] **Language packs** — Downloadable language packs to translate the app UI; allows multilingual teams to work in their native language
- [ ] **QuickBooks integration** — Sync cost tracking and financial data
- [ ] **Google Calendar sync** — Schedule and view batches on a calendar

---

## 🔵 Future / Enterprise

- [ ] **Predictive batch scheduling** — Use POS sales and pre-order data to suggest production increases; calendar alerts for time-sensitive prep (e.g. day-before cold ferment); requires POS integration first
- [ ] **Customer order tracking**
- [ ] **Inventory management**
- [ ] **Staff scheduling**
- [ ] **Equipment maintenance logs**
- [ ] **Multi-location dashboard support**
- [ ] **Role-based permissions** — Manager, supervisor, operator levels

